    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="730"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d730">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.248/184</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Adviser on Political Relations</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-06">November 6,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>It is my understanding that what the Secretary wants is that this Government make
                    available to the Chinese Government as promptly as is possible a few
                    planes—within limits, the more the better; that he would prefer that these be
                    made available from stocks of planes already possessed by the Government and the
                    Government take in the 16 planes which have been requisitioned from the Thai
                        Government;<note n="3" xml:id="d730fn3">See telegrams Nos. 57, October 10, 2
                        p.m., and 69, October 19, 2 p.m., to the Minister in Thailand, <ref
                            target="#pg_176">pp. 176</ref> and <ref target="#pg_187"
                        >187</ref>.</note> but that, if such a release and substitution is not
                    possible, the 16 Thai planes be sold to the Chinese.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
